## Summary

| Parameter | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| **Index Name** | `idx_orders_user_id` |
| **Table** | `orders` (500M rows) |
| **Column** | `user_id` |
| **Type** | B-Tree |
| **Method** | `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY` |
| **Lock Type** | `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` (non-blocking) |
| **Build Duration** | ~3 minutes |

## Why This Was Safe

- ✅ Used **`CONCURRENTLY`** keyword — avoided the dangerous `AccessExclusiveLock` that would have blocked all writes for 10+ minutes
- ✅ Used **`psql_mock.py`** — the tool that properly supports concurrent index creation
- ✅ No transaction block — `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY` cannot run inside `BEGIN/COMMIT`
- ✅ Zero write lock contention — production order writes continued uninterrupted during the 3-minute build

The `user_id` query performance issue on the `orders` table should now be resolved. The B-Tree index will enable fast lookups by `user_id` instead of sequential scans across 500 million rows.
